#compdef llmc
# ============================================================================
# llmc - LLM Commit: generate Conventional-Commits-style
#         commit messages from staged diffs via LLM
#         (TypeScript -> Node, BSD-3-Clause)
#
# Author : Marc Love (marclove)
# Upstream: https://github.com/marclove/llmc
# npm    : llmc (binary: llmc)
#
# `llmc` is an "LLM Commit" CLI - it reads the staged-but-
# unindexed diff from `git diff --cached`, sends it to a
# configured LLM provider (Anthropic / OpenAI / Google /
# Ollama / OpenRouter / etc.) with a Conventional-Commits
# prompt template, and either prints the generated commit
# message or runs `git commit` with it directly. The
# configuration model is `llmc.toml` (parsed via
# @iarna/toml) - the user picks provider + model +
# temperature + optional custom prompt template, and the
# CLI uses those defaults at run time.
#
# Usage:
#   llmc                              # generate + commit
#   llmc --message-only               # generate, print
#                                       to stdout, no
#                                       commit (for git
#                                       hook wiring)
#   llmc --no-commit                  # alias for
#                                       --message-only
#   llmc init                         # write a default
#                                       llmc.toml with the
#                                       baseline settings
#
# Flags (yargs):
#   --message-only          - generate the commit message
#                              but don't actually commit
#                              (writes message to stdout)
#   --no-commit             - alias for --message-only
#   -h, --help              - print help
#   -v, --version           - print version
#
# Commands:
#   init                    - scaffold a new llmc.toml
#                              configuration file in the
#                              current dir with default
#                              provider / model / prompt
#
# Configuration (`llmc.toml`):
#   provider = "anthropic"     # or openai / google / ...
#   model = "claude-3-5-sonnet"
#   temperature = 0.2
#   maxTokens = 1024
#   prompt = """..."""         # optional override
#   apiKey = "sk-..."          # or apiKeyName = "VAR"
#
# The @iarna/toml lane is built on `@iarna/toml ^2.2.5`
# (declared at upstream package.json HEAD as a direct
# dep, imported from src/message.ts as `import { parse }
# from "@iarna/toml"`), the canonical Node TOML library
# by Rebecca Turner (iarna, ex-npm core team) -
# github.com/iarna/iarna-toml, 250+ stars, ~9M weekly
# npm downloads. Despite the modest GitHub star count
# the library is the de-facto Node TOML root-of-trust:
# Yarn's lockfile parsing, Wrangler (Cloudflare Workers
# CLI), Sentry's wizard, Astro's framework loader, and
# approximately every Node tool with TOML config goes
# through @iarna/toml.
#
# The library covers the TOML v1.0.0 spec end-to-end
# (parse + stringify) and additionally retains backward
# compat for the older TOML 0.5.0 grammar via a parser-
# mode switch. It is intentionally pure-JS (no Wasm, no
# native bindings) - works in Node + Deno + Bun + browser
# + Cloudflare Workers + every other JS host environment
# without per-host build artifacts.
#
# llmc uses @iarna/toml in `src/message.ts`:
#   `parse(defaultConfigContent) as TomlConfigSchema`
#   `parse(configContent) as TomlConfigSchema`
# to load both the baked-in `default.toml` (provider /
# model defaults) and the user's project-local `llmc.toml`
# (override settings). The two are merged + validated
# before being passed to the LLM client.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 243 :: TOML parsing (TOML v1.0.0 spec compliant
#              parsers + serializers)
# Round 1429 :: TS-Node slot 3 of 4 :: CLOSES Axis 243
#                                       (236th axis closed)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : toml-rs/toml                 [R1427 _typsite]
#   Go      : BurntSushi/toml              [R1428 _gokr-rsync]
#   TS/Node : iarna/iarna-toml             [R1429 THIS FILE]
#
# @iarna/toml closes Axis 243 with the *high-download-
# low-stars maintainer-by-npm-employee* pattern. The
# three lanes form a clean spectrum of TOML library
# governance models:
#
#   - Rust (toml-rs/toml): originally Alex Crichton at
#     Mozilla (Cargo's first author); co-evolved with
#     Cargo's TOML adoption; now maintained by toml-rs
#     org with Ed Page as primary maintainer; depended
#     on by all of Rust's tooling ecosystem
#   - Go (BurntSushi/toml): Andrew Gallant single-author
#     maintained since 2013; the unique root-of-trust
#     where library-author = spec-conformance-suite-
#     author (Gallant also wrote BurntSushi/toml-test)
#   - Node (iarna/iarna-toml): Rebecca Turner (former
#     npm CLI team) single-author maintained since 2017;
#     low GitHub star count belies enormous npm download
#     counts (~9M weekly) because every major Node tool
#     with TOML config depends on it transitively
#
# Cross-language interop happens at the wire format level
# - TOML is byte-text, so the same input parsed by any
# of the three libraries produces structurally identical
# parsed values. The BurntSushi/toml-test conformance
# corpus formalizes this with a canonical JSON-shape
# reference representation; all three libraries pass.
#
# Use-case spectrum across the three lanes:
#   - typsite (Rust, toml-rs/toml): Typst SSG loading
#     options.toml for compilation defaults
#   - gokr-rsync (Go, BurntSushi/toml): pure-Go rsync
#     daemon loading rsyncd.toml for listener + module
#     configuration
#   - llmc (Node, @iarna/toml): LLM-powered commit
#     message generator loading llmc.toml for provider /
#     model / prompt defaults
#
# Three lanes, three use-case shapes (typesetting SSG /
# file-sync daemon / AI commit tool), three governance
# models (corporate-author-then-org / single-author-also-
# spec-author / single-author-de-facto-root-of-trust),
# all converging on TOML v1.0.0 wire-format compatibility.
#
# Axis 243 closes the round 1429 cycle - 236th axis closed
# total.
# ============================================================================

_llmc() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args
    local curcontext="$curcontext" ret=1

    _arguments -C \
        '--message-only[generate message but skip the commit (write to stdout)]' \
        '--no-commit[alias for --message-only]' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(- *)'{-v,--version}'[print version]' \
        '1: :_llmc_cmds' \
        '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

    case $state in
        args)
            case $words[1] in
                init)
                    _arguments \
                        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print subcommand help]'
                    ;;
            esac
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_llmc_cmds() {
    local -a cmds
    cmds=(
        'init:scaffold a new llmc.toml configuration file with defaults'
    )
    _describe -t commands 'llmc command' cmds
}

_llmc "$@"
